Today, thousands of students and staff accessed Aeries to allow us to test network connectivity and analyze our service provider‚Äôs systems. As a result some users experienced slower than normal service or service interruption. Therefore, tonight at 7:30 p.m. we will be turning off Aeries for a short time to make some enhancements to our system. We anticipate Aeries will be back online by 8:30 p.m. so students can check their class schedule and find the meeting links to join classes tomorrow.

Thank you for participating in our systems test this morning. Have a great first day of school.

The @HuntingtonBeachAPA completed its first-ever virtual pop music summer camp for children ages 9-15 earlier this month.

Students received an introduction to vocals and guitar, learned songwriting skills, and were given master classes on home recording, booking performances, and branding their individual sound. All instruction was led through online video communications, with students participating in a virtual "open mic" performance during the camp‚Äôs final meeting.

The first of its kind, APA's Plug-In to Pop Music Virtual Summer Camp was hosted by the Academy‚Äôs Music, Media and Entertainment Technology (MMET) Department, which is known for its songwriting-forward curriculum and large-scale student rock concerts.

Bill Kerwin - Director, Purchasing/Contracts/Risk Management

"We are resilient, determined, and capable during trying times...but what really makes things work during times like this is a sense of teamwork and collegiality...so stay positive, engaged, and excited about life!"
text:
Bill Kerwin - Director, Purchasing/Contracts/Risk Management

"We are resilient, determined, and capable during trying times...but what really makes things work during times like this is a sense of teamwork and collegiality...so stay positive, engaged, and excited about life!"

post_text:
Andrea Atkinson - EHS Assistant Principal

"One takeaway from this time is my conscious choice to pause and reflect...and look forward. I am usually a very 'in the moment' person, but the chaos of our world and the current situation has given me an opportunity to really reflect on this past year. Also, I am finding joy in working with my Edison staff on making plans and looking forward to next year! I can't wait to reconnect with all the students and staff in person!"

post_text:
Amy Sabol - WHS Principal

"Witnessing our staff, students, and community come together during this time to support each other has been inspiring. It is a true honor to work alongside such dedicated and compassionate people. I cannot wait to see our students filling our halls again, I miss them tremendously."

Robert Rasmussen - OVHS Assistant Principal

"Despite the current challenges, there is a lot to be thankful for. We have become stronger as a community, and despite the physical separation, we are united together through innovation and determination.

I am really looking forward to seeing our students and staff again. I miss seeing their faces and hearing their stories. Our school is definitely not the same without them!"

post_text:
Anil Muhammed - Director, Human Resources Classified

"During these unprecedented times, I've witnessed a great outpour of generosity from our classified employees. It's truly heartwarming to see so many of them serving on the front line to provide meals to students, sanitize our classrooms, and ensure safety of our campuses so that others can return to a safe and healthy environment. This notion of placing "others first" across the spectrum is what makes HBUHSD among the top workplaces in Orange County. More importantly, service to others is precisely why I joined classified service over 13 years ago."

Jaime Kerns is WHS's amazing nurse!‚ù§Ô∏èüñ§

"Since I have been away from WHS I have been reminded of how valuable my work and personal communities are in my life. post_text:
Annika Bodenhamer is MHS's amazing nurse!üíôüíõ

Principal Jessie Marion says, "We are so lucky to have Annika Bodenhamer as Marina's School Nurse. She is knowledgeable and supportive to both students and staff, and she is an all-around great team member!"

Annika has taken this time to appreciate home life, "As I reflect back on the last couple of months, I can honestly say that our family has grown stronger. We began this crisis filled with trepidation, but as the weeks rolled by, I began to notice little changes. Subtly, we all started gathering in the kitchen for meals again and began taking walks as a family. Suddenly every single dog in the neighborhood is getting walked, and people are greeting each other with waves and good cheer. In many ways, this has been a reset for all of us. What a great opportunity we have to be reminded of what is truly important, and I hope this time we don't forget."

OV's amazing nurse is JoAnne von Kotska.ü§©

OV's Principal, Courtney Robinson, is thrilled to say, "This year she was selected as the California School Nurses Organization-Southern Section‚Äôs Nurse of the Year and she is the State's Nominee for Excellence in School Nursing. JoAnne is always 'living the dream' and her passion for what she does is second to none. Students come first and she builds a strong rapport with all of them. She works so hard for our kids and we are extremely lucky to have her as our nurse!"

JoAnne is happy to see people coming together in this tough time, "It has been amazing how everyone has stepped up to provide help in any way they can to provide support for others as we deal with the pandemic."

post_text:
Catherine Lawlor from EHS is our next rockstar!üíöüíõ

"I am staying well connected with work friends and colleagues with lots of google meets, texts, chatting on the phone, and FaceTime. I enjoy the time I can spend at the office as I get to personally interact with some of my colleagues.

I am very much looking forward to seeing all the bright happy faces of co-workers and students, and to once again embrace all the excitement, noise, and chaotic fun vibe that comes from working at a high school site.

Everyone is struggling with this whole situation, some more than others. I am continually impressed with how my school community and colleagues show genuine compassion and concern for our students, community and for each other, striving every day to reach out and lend a kind helping hand.

I have been forced to be creative to find new yet efficient ways to complete my normal work duties. I have been pushed outside of my comfort zone and have discovered and learned a lot that I am excited to be able to continue to use as we move forward."

post_text:
Linh Nguyen from HBAS is next up!

"I‚Äôm looking forward to seeing students, teachers and staff again. There is something special about students saying good morning to you every day, teachers stopping by the office to chat and having conversations with coworkers. Being home every day reminds me how much I miss the personal interaction and how blessed I am to work for a great school.

I have a favorite quote: 'We can‚Äôt help everyone, but everyone can help someone.'
It reminds me that I may not have the capacity to help the entire world; let alone an entire school but I do have the ability to help at least one person in any way I can. Small acts of kindness can even be a smile. I believe focusing on helping each other, students and the community is the way to keep HOPE alive."

post_text:
Vanessa Rodriguez from HBAS is next!ü§©

"At Hbas we have an amazing team! Our staff has been moving forward using Microsoft Teams, Google Hangouts, and Zoom. Many of us created Google Voice phone numbers to text/call students who have not been engaging in online class meetings or who haven't responded to emails. We just want each of them to know that we are still here to support them in any way possible and to let them know we miss them and hope they are safe and healthy.

As for me, I've found joy and solace in spending time exercising outdoors. Normally I rely on the gym due to the lack of spare time and because it is so convenient, but nothing beats absorbing the wonders of nature on a hiking trail, or the breeze running along the beach. I'm excited to reconnect with my colleagues and all of our students on campus, hopefully in the fall, but for now I'm happy to know we can connect online and I'm glad everyone is getting creative and making the most of our current situation."

OVHS's Carolina Alferez helped create a hotline to help families with resources, and she helps our community at large. She organized a fundraiser to get supplies for neighborhood preschool students because the kids didn‚Äôt have what they needed at home. She has also been calling families who speak Spanish to help us out.üíõ

"These times have not been easy for any of us. My main priority during this time was to make sure that our community and students knew they could reach out to someone if they needed anything. Sometimes our community and students just need someone to talk to, to vent their frustrations and to share their life events; I always make sure to be there for them. My job is not just a job, it is my passion. Not being able to see our students everyday has been hard on me but I am truly looking forward to being able to continue to connect with them via email and google meets, but looking to being back on campus with them the most. "

post_text:
Janeen Schiavone keeps VvHS together with her amazing organizational skills & moreover her amazing support of the entire staff & at-promise students. She is the go to person at VvHS.

"I can't wait to get back to Valley Vista to see the staff and the students again. I miss my co-workers in the office, our wonderful teachers, and the amazing students we have at VvHS. Since our school is so small, the staff is really like a little family and it's been hard being away from my family for so long. I pride myself on trying to learn most of the students' names, and although I have considerably less interactions with our students than much of our staff, I really enjoy getting to know the students and connecting with them over something we have in common, like a favorite band or TV show. As much as I've enjoyed all the extra time I've been getting to spend with my dog while working from home, I'm looking forward to things returning to normal."

post_text:
Compass Center's Maggie Blade is our next superstar!

"I am grateful to work within the HBUHSD family during these unprecedented times. The support, flexibility, and positivity from the district, coworkers, families, and students has been incredible to help maintain a healthy and successful course to continue with academics as well as social emotional well being. Remember to self care and that distressful moments eventually end. Try to stay mindful in the present, keep positive, and maintain a sense of humor. We are all doing the best we can in the moment and is important to validate ourselves and others around us. Looking forward to continue working together to support one another's social emotional needs and academic success."

"I am staying connected a couple of ways. I am emailing students, using Google Meets for counseling sessions and using Google voice to text or call them. I've been staying in contact with staff pretty much the same way as the students, via email, texts, phone calls and Google Meets.

I am looking forward to seeing people! I miss being around students, hearing their laughter and listening to their struggles in person. I miss being around my amazing colleagues and our ability to support each other on a daily basis.

post_text:
Courtney Winford from CHS & HBAS is our next rockstar HBPSA employee!ü§©

"I miss the interaction with my team, we are all very close at both the Adult School and Coast High School, like family! I can't wait to be able to see all their faces again. I am also looking forward to connecting with my students in person.

I know that we are all going through a different struggle right now, but our school is here to support you and help lift you up during this time. Please try to look for the positives even if they are small and try to cling to those. I am cherishing this time that I am getting to spend with my son. I am appreciating not rushing around everywhere and that we are finally getting the time to do some of the special things that we have always wanted!

I just want to say that we have the BEST school district around and I am blessed to of been able to call it home for over 20 years as a Marina graduate, a Special Education teacher and now as a Counselor!"

Greg Berger from WHS is our next rockstar for his work with CTE and providing technology support during distance learning.

"I continue to call, text, and message staff through social media to learn how others are managing and offer help to stay connected. My students and I have been connecting regularly in Google Meet sessions and through eMail. I have even had the opportunity to see and speak to many students while distributing Senior Class apparel at our daily Grab & Go lunch line - you can't beat the feeling of a smile and a wave!

I can't wait to see students and teachers alike be excited to be in class, to interact with one another, and foster the ambitions that lead to fulfilling dreams.

Every tooth on every gear matters; it's our job to learn how to mesh with one another. Some of us move quickly, and others tick along at a snail's pace, others race by us like the wind...but we all have a role. We must all be committed to keeping this clock running!"

"I've been SO impressed with our students' Semper Gumbi (Always Flexible) attitudes! From creating "at-home xylophones" out of construction paper for practicing on, to stepping outside their comfort zones and posting singing videos online, to reaching out to our special needs musicians during this time away by hopping on our voluntary United Sound video calls - our students have proven their creative ingenuity, strength of character, and depth of caring in countless ways during this difficult time of distancing. As a teacher hoping to impart these qualities alongside the curriculum, I couldn't be more proud of what we're seeing in our students right now."

post_text:
VvHS's Meghann O'Connor has done an awesome job as co-coordinator for VvHS's WASC self study process and teaching the Leadership class that supports student activities.

"I can't wait to get back to school to SEE our students! There are so many things I miss like greeting all my students with "Hi, hello!" as they walk in and "Bye, have a good day, see ya later" on their way out, of course actual teaching, News Updates with my classes and at this point I even miss recycling!

One thing I have been so happy to see is so many people going out of their way to try and spread positivity around them. Whether it's chalk art/messages, neighborhood scavenger hunts, helping out their family and neighbors. I've always liked the Mr. Roger's quote "Look for the helpers. You will always find people who are helping." I've seen so many instances of students and the community helping in big and small ways! So to all my students, "Hi, hey, hello!" and hopefully we'll see each other soon!"

post_text:
Our next teacher is Becky Hernandez from MHS!üíôüíõ She can't wait to go back to school to be able to see her students' faces when she cracks corny jokes again.

"I've been using Google Meet a lot to connect with students and colleagues. I've been holding virtual office hours and a just for fun Kahoot 1-2 times per week with my classes. I also have unofficial Instagram pages for my US History and AP Art History classes just to share little updates, movies, and random life posts with my students.

What's one positive message/takeaway you would like to share with your students/community members?
This is not a normal time so don't be too hard on yourself. We should all be striving to be life-long learners and that might mean now, more than ever, that we are learning less from textbooks and more from real-life experiences. Reach out to your grandparents to ask about life in the 1960s, cook something from a WWII ration cookbook, do that art project on Fauvism."

OVHS's Andrew Martasian is our next rockstar for his hard work and dedication with OV's EL students.

"I‚Äôm staying connected with my colleagues via Facetime and regular group texts with my department. I‚Äôve been connecting with students on Canvas - at the end of every week my students answer a weekly check-in question and I make sure to respond to each student individually.

Positive takeaway: I‚Äôve used the extra time at home to do a variety of home improvement projects, such as gardening, cleaning out closets/the garage and painting. It has been nice to do a lot of these projects that I otherwise would not have had time for. As much as it is not fun that we can‚Äôt be together at school, this time at home is nice for doing personal projects and for connecting with people (via Facetime...not in person) that we otherwise might not have had time for during our previously busy lives. I‚Äôve also been reading a lot and am still trying to encourage my students to read as much as possible by sharing with them the list of books that I've read."

Edison High School PTSA
February 13 at 4:22 PM ¬∑

So proud of the students from HBUHSD that are participating in this great program!
Session #2 of the Huntington Union Council PTA's Student Advocacy Program, hosted by Edison High School & PTSA. This is the program's fourth year and student participation has grown from 8 students in year one to 40 students this year. The first week we kicked off the program with a session on how public education is financed in California. The topic for this week is Academics and related issues. Our Moderator Jason Ross had questions posed to the panel. He also encouraged the students to pose questions of their own and this topic gave robust participation.
